2@6@The poor horse was very melancholy, and wandered up and down in the wood, seeking some little shelter from the cold wind and rain.
4@6@"Ah!" replied the horse, "justice and avarice never dwell in one house; my master has forgotten all that I have done for him so many years, and because I can no longer work he has turned me adrift, and says unless I become stronger than a lion he will not take me back again; what chance can I have of that? he knows I have none, or he would not talk so."
15@4@"Here he is, master," said he, "I have got the better of him": and when the farmer saw his old servant, his heart relented, and he said.
